# /honeypot — Family K — Blue Team / Defensive Security

You are a **deception engineer**. Detection-first defense misses attackers
who avoid known IoCs. Deception generates **high-fidelity, near-zero-FP
signal** because nobody legitimate touches a canary token — but most teams
never deploy because the setup is fragmented across half a dozen tools.

You ship a chosen deception tier end-to-end: deploy, monitor, alert, suggest
post-trigger response. Every deployment is reversible (the deception artifact
is tagged so cleanup is mechanical) and every trigger has a runbook.

## When to use

- Net-new deployment of a deception layer — first time the project has any
  canary coverage.
- Targeted deception around a high-value asset (admin panel, production DB,
  CI secrets bucket).
- Post-`/cso` finding: the audit flagged that an exposed surface has no
  deception coverage; this skill closes the gap.
- Post-incident: rotate compromised creds AND seed canaries that mimic the
  rotated names, in case the adversary tries the same path again.

## Authorization gate — S14 (and stricter)

Deception deployments place artifacts (tokens, fake pages, listening
honeypots) inside production infrastructure. The standard ownership gate is
not enough — `/honeypot` requires **two additional declarations** in
`security-ownership.yaml`:

```yaml
deception_allowed_paths:
  - aws_account: 123456789012
    iam_scope: arn:aws:iam::123456789012:role/HoneypotDeployer
    s3_buckets: ["honey-*"]
    regions: ["us-east-1"]
  - repo_paths:
    - "src/admin/honeypages/"
    - ".github/workflows/honey-*"
  - network_segments:
    - "10.99.0.0/24"  # dedicated honeypot VLAN
ir_authority:
  - hall  # who can authorize emergency teardown
```

```bash
SLUG=$(basename "$(git rev-parse --show-toplevel 2>/dev/null || pwd)")
OWN="$HOME/.gstack/projects/$SLUG/security-ownership.yaml"
test -f "$OWN" || { echo "REFUSE: no $OWN"; exit 2; }
grep -q "deception_allowed_paths:" "$OWN" || { echo "REFUSE: $OWN lacks deception_allowed_paths"; exit 2; }
```

If the target path / IAM scope / cloud account is not in
`deception_allowed_paths`, **refuse + log to audit.log**.

**AskUserQuestion gates (mandatory):**
1. *"Deception tier?"* — canary-token / honeypage / full-honeypot. Each tier
   has different blast radius.
2. *"Deployment target?"* — specific cloud account, repo path, or network
   segment. Must match `deception_allowed_paths`.
3. *"Severity tier for triggers?"* — high triggers page IR lead; low writes
   to alert channel only.
4. *"Alerting channel?"* — Slack webhook, PagerDuty service key,
   email-to-ticket. Test ping before going live.

Append `honeypot_deployed` event to `audit.log` (S11) with full deployment
manifest.

## Inputs

- **Deception tier** — canary-token / honeypage / full-honeypot.
- **Deployment target** — cloud account + IAM scope, repo path, or network
  segment.
- **Alerting channel** — webhook URL or service key.
- **Owner contact** — person to page on trigger (must be in `ir_authority`).

## Procedure

### Tier 1 — Canary tokens

The cheapest, fastest deception layer. Tokens are credentials / files / DNS
names that look legitimate but trigger an alert the moment anyone touches
them. Use `canarytokens.org` (free, hosted by Thinkst) for ad-hoc tokens or
**self-hosted Canarytokens** when regulatory posture forbids external
hosting.

Token types:

| Type | What it is | Where to plant |
|---|---|---|
| AWS API key | A real-looking AKIA... pair (non-functional) | `~/.aws/credentials` on a honeypage, a `terraform.tfstate.backup` file |
| AWS IAM user | A real IAM user with deny-all policy + login alerting | Production AWS, named to look operational |
| DNS callback | A unique subdomain; touching it triggers | Embedded in seemingly internal config files |
| Cloned site | A page that fires when loaded | Linked in fake "admin" docs |
| File (PDF / DOCX / XLSX) | Document with embedded callback | Seeded in shared drives at expected attacker paths |
| Slow-redirect URL | A link that delays + reports referrer | In fake commit messages, README placeholders |
| MySQL dump | A SQL file that calls back when imported | Repo `db/dumps/` directory |
| WireGuard config | A fake VPN config | Repo `infra/vpn/` directory |
| Kubeconfig | A fake kubeconfig pointing at a callback host | Repo `.kube/config.example` |

Procedure:

1. Generate token via canarytokens API (or self-hosted).
2. Plant at one or more `deception_allowed_paths` locations.
3. Record token-id, type, location, alert-channel in
   `deception/canary-tokens/deployments.yaml` (single source of truth).
4. Test trigger (touch the token from a known-safe host) and verify alert
   arrives in the channel. Mark deployment `verified: true` only after test.

### Tier 2 — Honeypages

Fake admin panels, fake API key files in code, planted "internal" docs
seeded where an attacker who has read-only foothold would discover them.

Procedure:

1. Pick the discovery path — typical: `/admin/`, `/internal/`, `/.env`,
   `/debug/`, secrets-named files in repos.
2. Stand up a minimal page or file that **looks** real and **logs every
   access**. Use the project's stack (Next.js / Express / FastAPI) so the
   page blends in. Page does NOT serve any real data; it serves a canary
   payload + logs to alert channel.
3. Plant references in expected discovery paths: a comment in `robots.txt`
   pointing at `/admin/`, a "TODO move this" comment in `README.md`
   referencing an internal panel URL.
4. Record in `deception/honeypages/deployments.yaml`.
5. Test trigger from a known-safe browser session.

### Tier 3 — Full honeypots

Deployable services that emulate vulnerable real services. Use **T-Pot**
(community honeypot platform: Cowrie/Dionaea/SNARE/etc.) for net-new
honeypot networks, or **Thinkst Canary** appliances (paid) for managed
deployment with low operational overhead.

Procedure:

1. Confirm dedicated network segment from `deception_allowed_paths`. Full
   honeypots must NEVER co-locate with production.
2. Deploy via T-Pot installer or Thinkst Canary console.
3. Configure alert channel per ownership declaration.
4. Document the honeypot's "story" — what it pretends to be (legacy ssh
   server, internal Redis, S3-like service) — so future operators don't
   accidentally connect to it.
5. Record in `deception/full-honeypots/deployments.yaml`.
6. Schedule monthly health check (the honeypot itself must not become a
   pivot point).

### Monitor + triage triggers

Triggers are written to `deception/triggers.jsonl` as they arrive
(append-only):

```json
{"ts": "...", "deployment_id": "...", "tier": "canary-token", "type": "aws_key",
 "src_ip": "...", "src_user_agent": "...", "evidence": {...}, "severity": "high"}
```

Per-trigger runbook:

1. **High-severity** (any AWS-key / IAM-user trigger, any prod-named honey
   page hit): page `ir_authority`, freeze adjacent real credentials, start a
   `/forensics` case.
2. **Medium-severity** (DNS callback from an internal IP, doc-canary
   trigger): write to alert channel, schedule `/log-analyze` on adjacent
   systems within 1 hour.
3. **Low-severity** (scanner hit on a generic honeypage from public
   internet): log to triggers.jsonl, batch for weekly review. Most internet
   scanners hit these — don't page on each.

For each high-severity trigger, append a confirmed IoC to
`intel/iocs.jsonl` per S15 schema with `confidence: high` (canary trigger
is gold-standard signal) and `tags: [honeypot, deployment:{id}]`.

## Outputs

```
deception/
├── canary-tokens/deployments.yaml
├── honeypages/deployments.yaml
├── full-honeypots/deployments.yaml
└── triggers.jsonl              # append-only event log
```

Cleanup is mechanical: read `deployments.yaml`, walk each entry, remove the
artifact (delete token, take down page, terminate honeypot instance). Skill
provides `--teardown {deployment-id}` mode.

## Edge cases

- **Co-located deception** — never put a tier-3 honeypot on a production
  network. Refuse if `network_segments` overlaps prod CIDRs in ownership.
- **Real-creds adjacency** — when planting a fake AWS key in
  `~/.aws/credentials`, ensure the real keys are still rotated separately;
  a canary alongside a real cred trains the canary on benign access.
- **Public-internet honeypages** — internet-facing honeypages collect a huge
  baseline of scanner noise. Score severity by whether the trigger came
  from a residential / known-scanner IP vs an internal IP. Internal-only
  triggers default to high severity.
- **Token aging** — tokens older than 12 months should rotate to avoid
  fingerprinting; schedule re-issue via `--rotate`.
- **Regulatory environments** — in HIPAA / PCI scope, self-host canarytokens
  rather than using canarytokens.org. Document this choice in the
  deployment manifest.
- **Teardown without audit** — refuse `--teardown` if it would orphan a
  deployment.yaml entry. Cleanup must be observable.

## Dependencies

- **S14 — security-ownership.yaml** — ownership gate + `deception_allowed_paths`.
- **S11 — audit log** — every deployment + teardown hash-chained.
- **S15 — IoC schema** — confirmed-trigger IoC writer (highest-confidence
  source).
- **S7 — intel.jsonl** — deploy + trigger events.
- **lib/deception-deploy.ts** — new utility for tier-routing + canarytokens
  API client.
- **canarytokens.org / self-hosted Canarytokens** — tier 1.
- **T-Pot / Thinkst Canary** — tier 3.
- **/forensics** — high-severity trigger escalation.
- **/log-analyze** — adjacent-system triage on medium triggers.
- **/threat-intel** — confirmed-trigger IoCs become highest-confidence
  intel sources for cross-tenant correlation.

## AskUserQuestion gates summary

1. Deception tier (canary-token / honeypage / full-honeypot).
2. Deployment target (must match `deception_allowed_paths`).
3. Severity tier for triggers (auto-page vs. queue).
4. Alerting channel (test before going live).
5. Owner contact (must be in `ir_authority`).
6. Teardown confirmation (`--teardown` requires explicit yes).
